Nice!  I didn't think of using a context manager solution.

Unfortunately, as I feared, it doesn't work with Google App Engine web service.  The httplib module available doesn't have _MAXHEADERS.  

```
original_max_headers = httplib._MAXHEADERS 
AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute '_MAXHEADERS'
```
(OTOH, the "got more than 100 headers" error doesn't seem to happen in the web service version.)

I haven't done much with context managers--what would you suggest to handle this?  This is what comes to mind, but it feels overly verbose:
```
@contextlib.contextmanager
def httplib_max_headers(number):
    try:
        original_max_headers = httplib._MAXHEADERS
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = number
    except AttributeError:
        original_max_headers = None
    yield
    if original_max_headers is not None:
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = original_max_headers
```
This feels 'cleaner', but is arguably less pythonic:
```
@contextlib.contextmanager
def httplib_max_headers(number):
    if hasattr(httplib,'_MAXHEADERS'):
        original_max_headers = httplib._MAXHEADERS
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = number
        yield
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = original_max_headers
    else:
        yield
```
Or more efficiently like this:
```
if hasattr(httplib,'_MAXHEADERS'):
    @contextlib.contextmanager
    def httplib_max_headers(number):
        original_max_headers = httplib._MAXHEADERS
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = number
        yield
        httplib._MAXHEADERS = original_max_headers
else:
    @contextlib.contextmanager
    def httplib_max_headers(number):
        yield
```
All three work, but I like the last one best of the three.  Any other suggestions?

