@thomasaarholt Currently, `copy` will create instances with the same ID (so they do not create copies on the javascript side). `copy` is also just a shallow copy, so it will likely have references to the same traits, which would be why you are seeing them all behave as one.

Regarding the speed for looped creation, my guess is that serialization for sending ( + compression?) is where the time is being spent. There is a bit of overhead when creating many widgets, as each widget is communicated individually to the browser. There might be some improvements with Notebook master, as it doesn't use compression by default.

Another optimization could be to create your own widget `ButtonArray`, which just has a list/tuple of descriptions (the `on_click` callback could maybe include the description of the button pushed?). This way only one widget is synced across to the browser side. This would however require some JS code...

